  "description": "<section id=\"description\">\n<p>Let $φ$ be Euler's totient function, i.e. for a natural number $n$, $φ(n)$ is the number of $k$, $1 ≤ k ≤ n$, for which $gcd(k,n) = 1$.</p>\n<p>By iterating $φ$, each positive integer generates a decreasing chain of numbers ending in 1. E.g. if we start with 5 the sequence 5,4,2,1 is generated. Here is a listing of all chains with length 4:</p>\n<p>$$\\begin{align}\n5,4,2,1 &#x26; \\\\\n7,6,2,1 &#x26; \\\\\n8,4,2,1 &#x26; \\\\\n9,6,2,1 &#x26; \\\\\n10,4,2,1 &#x26; \\\\\n12,4,2,1 &#x26; \\\\\n14,6,2,1 &#x26; \\\\\n18,6,2,1 &#x26;\n\\end{align}$$</p>\n<p>Only two of these chains start with a prime, their sum is 12.</p>\n<p>What is the sum of all primes less than $40\\,000\\,000$ which generate a chain of length 25?</p>\n</section>",
